Date: 25 Jan 2007
From: Mary Marshall <tropical.forestry@btinternet.com>
Source: MLive.com [edited]
<http://www.mlive.com/newsflash/business/index.ssf?/base/news-41/1169760842239140.xml&storylist=mibusiness%3E%20&storylist=mibusiness>

Fish-killing virus confirmed in Lake Huron
-----------------------------------------------
An aquatic virus that doesn't harm people but kills fish has made its
way to Lake Huron, state officials said Thu 25 Jan 2007.
The Michigan Department of Natural Resources said it confirmed the
presence of viral hemorrhagic septicema, or VHS, in fish taken from
Thunder Bay and from waters off Rogers City and
Cheboygan. Previously, VHS had been found only in 2 of the Great
Lakes -- Ontario and Erie -- and in Lake St. Clair. But officials
have predicted the virus eventually would spread across the entire lake system.
Infected fish in Lake Huron include whitefish, walleye and Chinook
salmon. All are popular sport and commercial species.
"The continuing march of VHS through the waters of the Great Lakes is
a major challenge to our agency and our management options," DNR
Director Rebecca Humphries said.
Last October [2006], the U.S. Department of Agriculture (USDA) banned
shipments of 37 species of live fish from the Great Lakes states in a
bid to check the spread of VHS.
Responding to complaints that the measure was damaging the region's
fishing industry, the USDA's Animal and Plant Health Inspection
Service (APHIS) later modified its order. The agency now allows some
fish to be taken across state lines with proper documentation. The
agency is working with state officials to craft a long-term policy.
[Byline: John Flesher]
